M|references|```
M|references|Duration (days) = (Sample per variant × Number of variants) / (Daily traffic × % exposed)
M|references|```
M|references|**Scenario 1: High-traffic page**
M|references|- Need: 10,000 per variant (2 variants = 20,000 total)
M|references|- Daily traffic: 5,000 visitors
M|references|- 100% exposed to test
M|references|- Duration: 20,000 / 5,000 = **4 days**
M|references|**Scenario 2: Medium-traffic page**
M|references|- Need: 30,000 per variant (60,000 total)
M|references|- Daily traffic: 2,000 visitors
M|references|- 100% exposed
M|references|- Duration: 60,000 / 2,000 = **30 days**
M|references|**Scenario 3: Low-traffic with partial exposure**
M|references|- Need: 15,000 per variant (30,000 total)
M|references|- Daily traffic: 500 visitors
M|references|- 50% exposed to test
M|references|- Effective daily: 250
M|references|- Duration: 30,000 / 250 = **120 days** (too long!)
M|references|Even with sufficient sample size, run tests for at least:
M|references|- **1 full week**: To capture day-of-week variation
M|references|- **2 business cycles**: If B2B (weekday vs. weekend patterns)
M|references|- **Through paydays**: If e-commerce (beginning/end of month)
M|references|Avoid running tests longer than 4-8 weeks:
M|references|- Novelty effects wear off
M|references|- External factors intervene
M|references|- Opportunity cost of other tests
