M|references|With more than 2 variants (A/B/n tests), you need more sample:
M|references|| Variants | Multiplier |
M|references||----------|------------|
M|references|| 2 (A/B) | 1x |
M|references|| 3 (A/B/C) | ~1.5x |
M|references|| 4 (A/B/C/D) | ~2x |
M|references|| 5+ | Consider reducing variants |
M|references|**Why?** More comparisons increase chance of false positives. You're comparing:
M|references|- A vs B
M|references|- A vs C
M|references|- B vs C (sometimes)
M|references|Apply Bonferroni correction or use tools that handle this automatically.
M|references|**Problem**: Not enough sample to detect realistic effects
M|references|**Fix**: Be realistic about MDE, get more traffic, or don't test
M|references|**Problem**: Waiting for sample size when you already have significance
M|references|**Fix**: This is actually fine—you committed to sample size, honor it
M|references|**Problem**: Using wrong conversion rate for calculation
M|references|**Fix**: Use the specific metric and page, not site-wide averages
M|references|**Problem**: Calculating for full traffic, then analyzing segments
M|references|**Fix**: If you plan segment analysis, calculate sample for smallest segment
M|references|**Problem**: Dividing traffic too many ways
M|references|**Fix**: Prioritize ruthlessly, run fewer concurrent tests
M|references|Options when you can't get enough traffic:
M|references|1. **Increase MDE**: Accept only detecting larger effects (20%+ lift)
M|references|2. **Lower confidence**: Use 90% instead of 95% (risky, doc it)
M|references|3. **Reduce variants**: Test only the most promising variant
M|references|4. **Combine traffic**: Test across multiple similar pages
M|references|5. **Test upstream**: Test earlier in funnel where traffic is higher
M|references|6. **Don't test**: Make dec based on qualitative data instead
M|references|7. **Longer test**: Accept longer duration (weeks/months)
M|references|If you must check results before reaching sample size:
M|references|Statistical method that adjusts for multiple looks at data.
M|references|- High-risk changes
M|references|- Need to stop bad variants early
M|references|- Time-sensitive decisions
M|references|- Optimizely (Stats Accelerator)
M|references|- VWO (SmartStats)
M|references|- PostHog (Bayesian approach)
M|references|- More flexibility to stop early
M|references|- Slightly larger sample size requirement
M|references|- More complex analysis
M|references|```
M|references|Daily traffic to page: _____
M|references|Baseline conversion rate: _____
M|references|MDE I care about: _____
M|references|Sample needed per variant: _____ (from tables above)
M|references|Days to run: Sample / Daily traffic = _____
M|references|If days > 60: Consider alternatives
M|references|If days > 30: Acceptable for high-impact tests
M|references|If days < 14: Likely feasible
M|references|If days < 7: Easy to run, consider running longer anyway
